WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:05.318
Professor Ben Polak: All
right, so last time we were

00:00:05.318 --> 00:00:09.007
talking about The Investor Game
and this was a coordination

00:00:09.007 --> 00:00:10.630
game,
and we learned some things.

00:00:10.630 --> 00:00:12.918
I just want to recall some of
the things we learned so I can

00:00:12.918 --> 00:00:16.213
highlight them a bit.
One thing we learned was that

00:00:16.213 --> 00:00:20.110
communication can help in a
coordination game.

00:00:20.110 --> 00:00:23.794
So I forget who it was,
but someone down here who has

00:00:23.794 --> 00:00:27.619
disappeared, was our Jimmy
Stewart character and helped

00:00:27.619 --> 00:00:31.728
coordinate you on a better
equilibrium simply by suggesting

00:00:31.728 --> 00:00:36.440
what you should do.
There are two lessons here.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:48.060
One is this is very different
from the Prisoner's Dilemma.

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:51.864
So we learned the very first
time that in the Prisoner's

00:00:51.864 --> 00:00:54.770
Dilemma communication per se
won't help,

00:00:54.770 --> 00:00:57.308
but in the coordination
problem, which could be just as

00:00:57.308 --> 00:00:59.330
serious socially as a Prisoner's
Dilemma,

00:00:59.330 --> 00:01:02.380
in a coordination problem it
may well help.

00:01:02.380 --> 00:01:07.707
The reason it helps is you're
trying to coordinate onto a Nash

00:01:07.707 --> 00:01:10.685
Equilibrium.
One way to think about Nash

00:01:10.685 --> 00:01:14.260
Equilibria is that they are
self-enforcing agreements,

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:16.543
so provided that everyone
believes that everyone is going

00:01:16.543 --> 00:01:21.280
to go along with this agreement,
then everyone in fact will.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:24.236
I want to make another,
slightly more philosophical

00:01:24.236 --> 00:01:27.664
remark associated with this and
it's to do with the idea of

00:01:27.664 --> 00:01:30.180
"leadership."
So leadership is kind of a big

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:33.050
word that you see written
probably too often these days,

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:36.316
in too many newspaper articles,
and it probably comes up in too

00:01:36.316 --> 00:01:38.995
many Yale classes,
and I don't claim to know

00:01:38.995 --> 00:01:41.819
anything about leadership.
And I don't think Game Theory

00:01:41.819 --> 00:01:43.883
is going to contribute to
anything to understanding about

00:01:43.883 --> 00:01:47.319
leadership.
But one thing we can do is tell

00:01:47.319 --> 00:01:51.667
you where leadership may help.
In the coordination game,

00:01:51.667 --> 00:01:54.921
where the idea is to try and
get people to coordinate on a

00:01:54.921 --> 00:01:58.290
particular equilibria rather
than on another equilibria,

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:01.799
or worse still,
to be uncoordinated entirely.

00:02:01.799 --> 00:02:04.541
In those kind of games,
leadership can help

00:02:04.541 --> 00:02:06.989
tremendously.
A little bit of leadership can

00:02:06.989 --> 00:02:09.752
help tremendously.
So these games,

00:02:09.752 --> 00:02:15.983
these coordination games,
are games where there is a

00:02:15.983 --> 00:02:20.522
"scope for leadership."
Just to see that in a very

00:02:20.522 --> 00:02:22.672
simple example,
again, we don't use such a

00:02:22.672 --> 00:02:25.659
complicated example as the one
we looked at last time,

00:02:25.659 --> 00:02:32.016
you could imagine a game,
a really trivial coordination

00:02:32.016 --> 00:02:38.490
game, which looked like this
(1,1) (0,0) (0,0) (1,1).

00:02:38.490 --> 00:02:43.139
And clearly in this game what
matters is coordinating.

00:02:43.139 --> 00:02:46.566
You either want to coordinate
on up left or you want to

00:02:46.566 --> 00:02:51.414
coordinate on down right.
You don't want to end up

00:02:51.414 --> 00:02:56.640
uncoordinated on down left or up
right.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.753
Everyone see that?
So in this game if you just

00:02:58.753 --> 00:03:01.131
played it, it's quite likely
you're going to end up

00:03:01.131 --> 00:03:03.641
uncoordinated,
but if you have a little bit of

00:03:03.641 --> 00:03:06.661
leadership can say okay let's
make sure this is where we

00:03:06.661 --> 00:03:09.089
coordinate,
or let's make sure this is

00:03:09.089 --> 00:03:11.539
where we coordinate.
So this matters a lot.

00:03:11.539 --> 00:03:15.306
And I don't want to overplay
the social importance of this,

00:03:15.306 --> 00:03:19.007
but go back a couple of years
to what was happening in the

00:03:19.007 --> 00:03:22.968
aftermath of Katrina and realize
how important--how bad things

00:03:22.968 --> 00:03:25.889
get when things fail to be
coordinated.

00:03:25.889 --> 00:03:28.763
One other remark before we
leave this, in the game we

00:03:28.763 --> 00:03:31.139
played last time,
