Coca-Cola manager is going
to--may be we should just make

01:00:40.109 --> 01:00:44.509
this Coke and Pepsi since two
identical--they're near enough

01:00:44.509 --> 01:00:46.570
and identical,
right?

01:00:46.570 --> 01:00:49.130
So these are Coke and Pepsi,
that will confuse me less.

01:00:49.130 --> 01:00:52.473
So Patrick, our manager of
Pepsi believes that Coca-Cola is

01:00:52.473 --> 01:00:55.990
going to produce this quantity
and he's agreed to produce this

01:00:55.990 --> 01:00:58.102
quantity.
What is Patrick actually going

01:00:58.102 --> 01:00:59.999
to do?
Patrick, what are you going to

01:00:59.999 --> 01:01:01.465
do?
Student: So I should

01:01:01.465 --> 01:01:04.162
cheat and pick the quantity on
my best response line that's

01:01:04.162 --> 01:01:06.860
much farther out so I'll produce
more than my quantity.

01:01:06.860 --> 01:01:08.799
Professor Ben Polak: All
right, so Patrick (being Jimmy

01:01:08.799 --> 01:01:11.279
Stewart or not,
actually) when he's in

01:01:11.279 --> 01:01:16.216
the--when he's playing the
manager of Pepsi he's going to

01:01:16.216 --> 01:01:21.858
produce more of this undrinkable
liquid and produce this quantity

01:01:21.858 --> 01:01:23.800
here.
So what is this?

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:32.332
This is Patrick's best response
to the other guy producing the

01:01:32.332 --> 01:01:37.099
monopoly quantity.
So Patrick's response in Pepsi

01:01:37.099 --> 01:01:40.579
is to overproduce relative to
the monopoly quantity,

01:01:40.579 --> 01:01:44.941
actually overproduce even
relative to the Cournot quantity

01:01:44.941 --> 01:01:47.619
and produce all the way out
here.

01:01:47.619 --> 01:01:53.207
Okay, so Patrick's producing
here but what about Mr.

01:01:53.207 --> 01:01:55.380
Coca-Cola guy?
Now, Mr.

01:01:55.380 --> 01:01:58.481
Coca-Cola guy knows Patrick
pretty well, they've been in the

01:01:58.481 --> 01:02:00.163
same industry for a while and
Mr.

01:02:00.163 --> 01:02:01.950
Coca-Cola guy,
whose name is?

01:02:01.950 --> 01:02:03.165
Student: Steven.
Professor Ben Polak:

01:02:03.165 --> 01:02:05.831
Steven.
Steven presumably knows that

01:02:05.831 --> 01:02:11.129
Patrick is actually going to
produce this quantity--I'm sorry

01:02:11.129 --> 01:02:14.019
this quantity.
So Steven, what should you

01:02:14.019 --> 01:02:16.112
produce?
Student: Increase my own

01:02:16.112 --> 01:02:18.349
production to match my best
response line.

01:02:18.349 --> 01:02:20.797
Professor Ben Polak:
Good, so Steven,

01:02:20.797 --> 01:02:24.099
anticipating that Patrick is
going to think that Steven's a

01:02:24.099 --> 01:02:27.343
sucker but Patrick's going to
cheat on him and produce too

01:02:27.343 --> 01:02:30.184
much,
Steven's going to produce a

01:02:30.184 --> 01:02:35.103
best response to that and he's
going to produce this quantity

01:02:35.103 --> 01:02:37.400
here.
So what is this?

01:02:37.400 --> 01:02:44.705
This is Player 2's best
response, so Player 1's best

01:02:44.705 --> 01:02:52.440
response to Player 2 producing
half monopoly output.

01:02:52.440 --> 01:02:54.139
But Patrick knows Steven pretty
well;

01:02:54.139 --> 01:02:57.349
he knows those guys who run
Coca-Cola are pretty smart guys,

01:02:57.349 --> 01:03:00.559
so Patrick knows that the guy
who runs Coca-Cola is going to

01:03:00.559 --> 01:03:03.932
anticipate that the guy who runs
Pepsi is going to cheat on the

01:03:03.932 --> 01:03:06.596
guy who runs Coca-Cola,
and hence the guy who runs

01:03:06.596 --> 01:03:09.103
Coca-Cola is going to play a
best response to Patrick's cheat

01:03:09.103 --> 01:03:12.501
on quantity.
So what quantity is Patrick

01:03:12.501 --> 01:03:15.314
going to produce?
Student: I'll increase

01:03:15.314 --> 01:03:17.526
my production then;
I'll be pretty close to the

01:03:17.526 --> 01:03:19.758
Cournot equilibrium.
Professor Ben Polak: All

01:03:19.758 --> 01:03:21.019
right, so you're going to go to
here;

01:03:21.019 --> 01:03:23.570
so this point here is--I can't
even write this.

01:03:23.570 --> 01:03:28.262
This is the best response of
Player 1 to the best response of

01:03:28.262 --> 01:03:32.407
Player 2, to the best response
of Player 1 to Player 2

01:03:32.407 --> 01:03:37.099
producing half monopoly output
and there are lots of brackets

01:03:37.099 --> 01:03:40.686
here.
Can anyone see where this

01:03:40.686 --> 01:03:45.255
process is going?
It's going back to the Nash

01:03:45.255 --> 01:03:47.710
Equilibrium.
Each of them is trying to play

01:03:47.710 --> 01:03:50.030
a best response for what they
anticipate the other person's

01:03:50.030 --> 01:03:52.120
going to do.
And in this game if they keep

01:03:52.120 --> 01:03:54.432
on doing that,
it's going to drag them back to

01:03:54.432 --> 01:03:56.520
Nash Equilibrium.
But I want to be careful here.

01:03:56.520 --> 01:03:59.055
This won't be true of all games.
But in this game,

01:03:59.055 --> 01:04:02.556
playing best response to each
other, figuring out that in fact

01:04:02.556 --> 01:04:04.909
the other guy is going to cheat
on me,

01:04:04.909 --> 01:04:06.400
or the other guy is
anticipating that I'm going to

01:04:06.400 --> 01:04:07.648
cheat on him,
or the other guy is going to

01:04:07.648 --> 01:04:09.382
anticipate that I'm going to
anticipate that he's going to

01:04:09.382 --> 01:04:12.264
cheat on me,
etc., etc., will eventually

01:04:12.264 --> 01:04:15.550
drag us back to the Cournot
quantity.

01:04:15.550 --> 01:04:18.654
So it's going to be pretty
difficult for us to sustain this

01:04:18.654 --> 01:04:21.329
joint monopoly output,
this collusive agreement.

01:04:21.329 --> 01:04:24.110
We can't let the courts enforce
it.

01:04:24.110 --> 01:04:26.614
We're Coca-Cola and Pepsi,
so we really don't want to have

01:04:26.614 --> 01:04:28.503
to bring the mafia in,
although maybe we do,

01:04:28.503 --> 01:04:30.264
I don't know.
So basically,

01:04:30.264 --> 01:04:34.712
we're stuck with this verbal
agreement and we both have an

01:04:34.712 --> 01:04:38.613
incentive to cheat and produce
more whatever it is,

01:04:38.613 --> 01:04:41.222
sugar water.
Now, in practice,

01:04:41.222 --> 01:04:45.674
this is not the only problem
facing two firms who are trying

01:04:45.674 --> 01:04:49.213
to produce the monopoly output.
In practice,

01:04:49.213 --> 01:04:53.593
when firms try and have these
agreements, which are not

01:04:53.593 --> 01:04:57.730
contracts, to try and produce
joint monopoly output,

01:04:57.730 --> 01:05:01.324
what else goes wrong?
So you can imagine some firms

01:05:01.324 --> 01:05:04.549
trying to have an agreement.
We know they can't sign a legal

01:05:04.549 --> 01:05:07.130
agreement, but let's take that
off the table.

01:05:07.130 --> 01:05:09.738
So, for example,
in around 1900 in America or a

01:05:09.738 --> 01:05:12.460
little bit earlier,
let's say 1880 in America,

01:05:12.460 --> 01:05:15.516
it really isn't clear that it
was illegal to write agreements

01:05:15.516 --> 01:05:17.300
to say we'll restrict
quantities.

01:05:17.300 --> 01:05:20.287
So firms did use to write that
kind of agreements,

01:05:20.287 --> 01:05:24.139
but still something went wrong.
What went wrong?

01:05:24.139 --> 01:05:26.493
So we're getting a little bit
further away from the game and

01:05:26.493 --> 01:05:29.090
more back into the real world.
What kind of things went wrong?

01:05:29.090 --> 01:05:31.110
I want to get somebody who's
near a mike.

01:05:31.110 --> 01:05:36.610
Can I get the woman here with
the Yale shirt?

01:05:36.610 --> 01:05:38.761
Student: Without a
contract there's no means of

01:05:38.761 --> 01:05:40.527
enforcement.
Professor Ben Polak: All

01:05:40.527 --> 01:05:42.458
right, so it might be
that--again, the problem with

01:05:42.458 --> 01:05:44.389
enforcement--although actually
in 1880 America,

01:05:44.389 --> 01:05:47.343
it's not clear that they
couldn't have enforced that

01:05:47.343 --> 01:05:48.889
contract.
So one problem is

01:05:48.889 --> 01:05:51.779
unenforceability but that
might--far off ago that might

01:05:51.779 --> 01:05:53.900
have been a problem.
What else?

01:05:53.900 --> 01:05:59.607
The guy next to her.
Student: If they're not

01:05:59.607 --> 01:06:02.905
at the competitive output they
could undercut price and take

01:06:02.905 --> 01:06:04.565
the entire market.
Professor Ben Polak:

01:06:04.565 --> 01:06:06.215
Let's be careful.
We'll come back to that next

01:06:06.215 --> 01:06:08.630
time, but right now we're
competing in quantities.

01:06:08.630 --> 01:06:11.054
So we're not fixing prices
here, we're not even naming

01:06:11.054 --> 01:06:13.187
price.
We're just producing Coca-Cola

01:06:13.187 --> 01:06:16.664
and Pepsi and for want of a
better word, spewing it out into

01:06:16.664 --> 01:06:21.900
the market.
What else goes wrong here?

01:06:21.900 --> 01:06:25.307
Well, one thing that goes wrong
is that suppose Coke and Pepsi

01:06:25.307 --> 01:06:28.826
were able to--either to write a
contract or whatever--to sustain

01:06:28.826 --> 01:06:31.340
joint monopoly output at this
high price,

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:33.661
this price which is
actually--producing positive

01:06:33.661 --> 01:06:36.179
profits in the industry--it is
going to turn out,

01:06:36.179 --> 01:06:38.780
therefore the price is going to
be above costs.

01:06:38.780 --> 01:06:41.481
These firms're making all the
profits, what do you thinks

01:06:41.481 --> 01:06:43.170
going to happen in this
industry?

01:06:43.170 --> 01:06:45.409
This industry that's got a lot
of profit around it,

01:06:45.409 --> 01:06:47.289
what's going to happen in this
industry?

01:06:47.289 --> 01:06:50.320
Yeah, the guy in the blue shirt
here;

01:06:50.320 --> 01:06:55.111
Ale this guy here.
Student: Another

01:06:55.111 --> 01:06:56.059
competitor could join the
market.

01:06:56.059 --> 01:06:58.731
Professor Ben Polak:
Another firm is going to come in

01:06:58.731 --> 01:07:00.578
and produce a similar product.
So Dr.

01:07:00.578 --> 01:07:02.900
Pepper or something,
is there one?

01:07:02.900 --> 01:07:05.916
Someone else is going to come
in and produce cola in this

01:07:05.916 --> 01:07:08.880
industry and that's exactly what
happened in the U.S.

01:07:08.880 --> 01:07:11.270
at the turn of the last century.
Companies did produce

01:07:11.270 --> 01:07:13.054
agreements to restrict,
for example,

01:07:13.054 --> 01:07:15.909
the production of paper and the
production of rubber,

01:07:15.909 --> 01:07:19.541
and the production of steel,
and the production of iron,

01:07:19.541 --> 01:07:22.050
and the production of railway
lines,

01:07:22.050 --> 01:07:23.900
actually, even quite
complicated things.

01:07:23.900 --> 01:07:27.349
Sure enough what you see very
quickly emerging is new entrants

01:07:27.349 --> 01:07:30.813
entering the market to say,
hey these firms are restricting

01:07:30.813 --> 01:07:33.460
their quantities,
we can get in there and make

01:07:33.460 --> 01:07:35.968
money.
So new and a competitive fringe

01:07:35.968 --> 01:07:39.159
of firms is going to enter and
drive prices down.

01:07:39.159 --> 01:07:42.262
Now, I'm talking about 1900
America where has that happened

01:07:42.262 --> 01:07:44.670
in the twentieth century more
dramatically?

01:07:44.670 --> 01:07:48.002
We know the early example in
sort of Golden Age America,

01:07:48.002 --> 01:07:51.395
but where else did we see a
competitive fringe enter when

01:07:51.395 --> 01:07:54.667
there was a collusive agreement
to keep prices--to keep

01:07:54.667 --> 01:07:57.179
quantities down?
Student: Airlines.

01:07:57.179 --> 01:08:00.090
Professor Ben Polak:
Good, so airlines is an example;

01:08:00.090 --> 01:08:01.670
we've seen that.
Where else?

01:08:01.670 --> 01:08:03.470
Oil is probably the classic
example.

01:08:03.470 --> 01:08:06.500
Airlines is a good example.
Okay, so in oil we all know

01:08:06.500 --> 01:08:09.304
that in the late 60s,
early 70s, OPEC was formed

01:08:09.304 --> 01:08:12.825
precisely to restrict quantity
among the major oil producing

01:08:12.825 --> 01:08:15.053
countries,
and very quickly we see

01:08:15.053 --> 01:08:18.646
companies take--other countries
take advantage of this to start

01:08:18.646 --> 01:08:23.937
producing oil profitably.
So who were the competitive

01:08:23.937 --> 01:08:28.529
fringe against OPEC?
Anybody?

01:08:28.529 --> 01:08:32.138
The Brits were for a start,
the Brits--England sort

01:08:32.138 --> 01:08:35.475
of--Scotland I should say.
Britain anyway started

01:08:35.475 --> 01:08:39.275
producing oil in the North Sea;
lots of countries in Latin

01:08:39.275 --> 01:08:43.191
America started looking and
finding oil, and of course,

01:08:43.191 --> 01:08:46.890
Russian oil started being very,
very profitable.

01:08:46.890 --> 01:08:50.377
So there are various reasons
why it's hard to maintain this

01:08:50.377 --> 01:08:53.401
collusive agreement.
One is there's an incentive to

01:08:53.401 --> 01:08:56.689
cheat and another is that other
firms are going to enter.

01:08:56.689 --> 01:08:59.569
Before we leave this,
let's just pose the question we

01:08:59.569 --> 01:09:01.547
started with.
Suppose, in fact,

01:09:01.547 --> 01:09:04.449
we do end up back at the
Cournot quantity.

01:09:04.449 --> 01:09:07.939
So here we are back at the
Cournot quantity.

01:09:07.939 --> 01:09:12.079
How does this quantity compare
and how do therefore the prices

01:09:12.079 --> 01:09:16.016
compare, and how do profits
compare with monopoly prices on

01:09:16.016 --> 01:09:19.602
the one hand,
and competitive prices on the

01:09:19.602 --> 01:09:22.261
other?
So we know the quantity that's

01:09:22.261 --> 01:09:24.540
going to be produced.
We figured that out;

01:09:24.540 --> 01:09:28.902
here it is.
We know the quantities going to

01:09:28.902 --> 01:09:34.256
be produced.
Each firm is going to produce a

01:09:34.256 --> 01:09:40.010
- c over 3b and there are two
such firms.

01:09:40.010 --> 01:09:48.742
So the total quantity produced
in the market--the total

01:09:48.742 --> 01:09:55.848
quantity will be 2a - c over 3b.
How does that compare to the

01:09:55.848 --> 01:10:00.123
monopoly quantity?
Well, the monopoly quantity was

01:10:00.123 --> 01:10:05.360
a - c over 2b and the
competitive quantity was a - c

01:10:05.360 --> 01:10:11.829
over b, just to remind you of
those, they're on our picture.

01:10:11.829 --> 01:10:19.420
Here's a - c over 2b and here's
a - c over b.

01:10:19.420 --> 01:10:22.201
So this is the total quantity
produced on this equilibrium,

01:10:22.201 --> 01:10:23.880
in this Cournot Nash
Equilibrium.

01:10:23.880 --> 01:10:30.756
How did it compare to the
monopoly quantity and to the

01:10:30.756 --> 01:10:36.439
competitive quantity?
Anybody?

01:10:36.439 --> 01:10:38.800
Just staring at the board,
which is of these is bigger?

01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:44.668
So I claim that this total
quantity being produced is less

01:10:44.668 --> 01:10:50.434
than the competitive quantity,
but more in total than the

01:10:50.434 --> 01:10:54.235
monopoly quantity.
I was about to get them the

01:10:54.235 --> 01:10:56.939
wrong way around.
Total quantity being produced

01:10:56.939 --> 01:11:00.183
is less than would be produced
under perfect competition,

01:11:00.183 --> 01:11:03.079
but more than would be produced
under monopoly.

01:11:03.079 --> 01:11:05.447
Consequently,
prices are going to go the

01:11:05.447 --> 01:11:08.846
other way and consequently
prices are going to be highest

01:11:08.846 --> 01:11:12.460
under monopoly,
lowest on the competition,

01:11:12.460 --> 01:11:17.380
and somewhere in between in
this Cournot situation.

01:11:17.380 --> 01:11:20.365
So from the point of view of
the producers,

01:11:20.365 --> 01:11:23.706
this Cournot Equilibrium is
worse than monopoly,

01:11:23.706 --> 01:11:26.550
but better than perfect
competition.

01:11:26.550 --> 01:11:29.735
And from the point of view of
the rest of us,

01:11:29.735 --> 01:11:32.920
the consumers,
this Cournot quantity is worse

01:11:32.920 --> 01:11:36.829
than perfect competition but
better than monopoly.

01:11:36.829 --> 01:11:39.595
The only rider on that being,
if they're producing Coca-Cola

01:11:39.595 --> 01:11:41.939
and you have any kind of concern
for your teeth,

01:11:41.939 --> 01:11:46.590
maybe you shouldn't produce so
much anyway.

01:11:46.590 --> 01:11:50.103
So, so far what we've done is
we've looked at this sort of

01:11:50.103 --> 01:11:53.739
classic, I admit not the most
exciting game in the world,

01:11:53.739 --> 01:11:57.640
but classic application of Game
Theory to imperfect competition.

01:11:57.640 --> 01:12:00.472
Next time I'm actually going to
take this a bit further but I'm

01:12:00.472 --> 01:12:03.304
going to leave this game behind
and look at other ways in which

01:12:03.304 --> 01:12:06.000
we could study imperfect
competition using Game Theory.

